2  a317 pages ;c21 cm  atext2rdacontent  aunmediated2rdamedia  avolume2rdacarrier  a"A Tom Doherty Associates book." 0aSpace warfarevFiction. 0aHuman-alien encountersvFiction. 7aScience fiction.2gsafd04145cam  2200409 i 1813273520150225154429.0140429s2014    nyu           000 1 eng    a7bcbccorignewd1eecipf20gy-gencatlg0 aacquireb1 shelf copyxpolicy defaulteclaim1  2014-12-29  bxk10 2014-04-29ixk10 2014-04-29 to CIP (Dewey complete)axn12 2015-02-11 1 copy rec'd., to CIP ver.fxk23 2015-02-25 to CALM  a  2014015247  a9780765375865 (cloth)  z9781466849358 (e-book)  aDLCbengcDLCerdadDLC  apcc00aPS3619.C256bL63 201400a813/.6223  aFIC0280002bisacsh1 aScalzi, John,d1969-10aLock in /cJohn Scalzi. 1aNew York :bTor, a Tom Doherty Associates Book,c2014.  a336 pages ;c22 cm  atext2rdacontent  aunmediated2rdamedia  avolume2rdacarrier  a"Fifteen years from now, a new virus sweeps the globe. 95% of those afflicted experience nothing worse than fever and headaches. Four percent suffer acute meningitis, creating the largest medical crisis in history. And one percent find themselves "locked in"--fully awake and aware, but unable to move or respond to stimulus.  One per cent doesn't seem like a lot. But in the United States, that's 1.7 million people "locked in"...including the President's wife and daughter.  Spurred by grief and the sheer magnitude of the suffering, America undertakes a massive scientific initiative. Nothing can restore the ability to control their own bodies to the locked in. But then two new technologies emerge. One is a virtual-reality environment, "The Agora," in which the locked-in can interact with other humans, both locked-in and not. The other is the discovery that a few rare individuals have brains that are receptive to being controlled by others, meaning that from time to time, those who are locked in can "ride" these people and use their bodies as if they were their own.  This skill is quickly regulated, licensed, bonded, and controlled. Nothing can go wrong. Certainly nobody would be tempted to misuse it, for murder, for political power, or worse....John Scalzi's Lock In is a novel of our near future, from one of the most popular authors in modern science fiction"--cProvided by publisher.  a"Fifteen years from now, a new virus sweeps the globe. 95% of those afflicted experience nothing worse than fever and headaches. Four percent suffer acute meningitis, creating the largest medical crisis in history. And one percent find themselves "locked in"--fully awake and aware, but unable to move or respond to stimulus. One per cent doesn't seem like a lot. But in the United States, that's 1.7 million people "locked in"...including the President's wife and daughter. Spurred by grief and the sheer magnitude of the suffering, America undertakes a massive scientific initiative. Nothing can restore the ability to control their own bodies to the locked in. But then two new technologies emerge. One is a virtual-reality environment, "The Agora," in which the locked-in can interact with other humans, both locked-in and not. The other is the discovery that a few rare individuals have brains that are receptive to being controlled by others, meaning that from time to time, those who are locked in can "ride" these people and use their bodies as if they were their own. This skill is quickly regulated, licensed, bonded, and controlled. Nothing can go wrong. Certainly nobody would be tempted to misuse it, for murder, for political power, or worse..."--cProvided by publisher. 0aVirus diseasesvFiction. 0aEpidemicsvFiction. 0aIsolation (Hospital care)vFiction. 0aVirtual realityvFiction. 0aParanormal fiction. 7aFICTION / Science Fiction / General.2bisacsh 7aHorror fiction.2gsafd 7aScience fiction.2gsafd423Cover imageuhttp://www.netread.com/jcusers2/bk1388/865/9780765375865/image/lgcover.9780765375865.jpg01004cam  2200289 